{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508175"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2730"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2730"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.54,0.1,0.29,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79114"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2730","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2730"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2730"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64466"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"464"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2560"},{"type":"tags","id":"11198"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3510"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3574"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79114"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents with a six month history of progressive weakness in both her arms and legs. She is most weak on exertion and finds it improves following rest and sleep. She has begun limiting her daily exertion and takes the lift instead of the stairs at work and has stopped cooking and carrying shopping bags. She has a past history of eczema and seasonal rhinitis. She does not smoke cigarettes but consumes 3-4 standard alcoholic drinks per week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 124/80mmHg, pulse rate 77/min, respiratory rate 16//min and SpO2 99% on room air. Her gait is symmetrical with quick turns. In her upper limbs she has no spasticity, reduced power in shoulder abduction only (4/5), symmetrical biceps and triceps reflexes (2+), and no intention tremor or dysdiadokokinesis. In her lower limbs she has no spasticity, preserved power, symmetrical patella and ankle reflexes (2+) and normal coordination. However she is unable to squat. Her sensation is intact for all modalities (paint, temperature, vibration and proprioception) in all limbs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be found on physical examination?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dilated pupils","Ptosis","Rash","Muscle wasting","Wheeze"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has clinical features consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Emyasthenia gravis (MG)\u003C/strong\u003E. Her \u003Cstrong\u003Eprogressive proximal muscle weakness\u003C/strong\u003E (worst on exertion and relieved by rest) is characteristic (her proximal muscles are affected as she cannot climb stairs or squat and has weak shoulder abduction). The weakness of MG is classically \u003Cstrong\u003Efatiguable\u003C/strong\u003E. It can involve the eyes and cause \u003Cstrong\u003Eptosis (ocular MG)\u003C/strong\u003E. MG can be mild, moderate or severe (as well as ocular or generalised).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMG causes ptosis most commonly, however it can also involve the extraocular muscles leading to diplopia. Pupillary examination is usually normal in MG and this is a good test to differentiate MG from an oculomotor cranial nerve palsy (which causes ptosis and a \u003Cstrong\u003Edilated pupil\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile a \u003Cstrong\u003Erash\u003C/strong\u003E is possible given her history of eczema, a rash is not a feature in MG. Dermatomyositis is an another cause of myopathic weakness that can have skin manifestations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile MG can involve respiratory muscles, it is unlikely to cause a \u003Cstrong\u003Ewheeze\u003C/strong\u003E through this mechanism. Lambert-Eaton syndrome is a disease which can present similarly to MG and can be associated with lung cancer, but even then lung cancer is unlikely to cause a wheeze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle wasting\u003C/strong\u003E is not a feature of MG. Muscle wasting can occur in other causes of weakness such as lower motor neurone pathologies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The positive signs usually associated with myasthenia gravis include proximal fatigue associated muscle weakness, which can also cause ptosis.","Symptoms/signs that may lead to suspicion of a non-myasthenia gravis pathology and require further examination would include dilation of the pupils, rash, wheeze, and muscle wasting.","Neurological examination signs that may be present in a patient with myasthenia gravis include possible reduced power and fatigability, normal reflexes (+2), normal coordination, no tremor, no spasticity, no dysdiadokokinesis, and symmetrical presentation of signs."],"references":["Tgldcdp.tg.org.au. 2021. Myasthenia gravis, including ocular myasthenia. [online] Available at: \u003Chttps://tgldcdp.tg.org.au/viewTopic?topicfile=myasthenia-gravis-including-ocular-myasthenia\u0026guidelineName=Neurology\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#MPS_d1e382\u003E [Accessed 29 July 2021].","Behbehani R. Ocular Myasthenia Gravis: A Current Overview. Eye Brain. 2023 Feb 5;15:1-13. doi: 10.2147/EB.S389629. PMID: 36778719; PMCID: PMC9911903. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9911903/","Nair AG, Patil-Chhablani P, Venkatramani DV, Gandhi RA. Ocular myasthenia gravis: a review. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2014 Oct;62(10):985-91. doi: 10.4103/0301-4738.145987. PMID: 25449931; PMCID: PMC4278125. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4278125/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64466"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2730"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64466"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:08:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:08:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2730"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79114"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":